d of this book resulting in a decision tree. Polish is not investigated in isolation, however, the study is complemented by comparisons with other Slavic languages and also with a Polish dialect called 'Upper Silesian', which differs from Polish. The analysis in this book is based on Löbner's theory of 'Concept Types and Determination' (CTD). Löbner's distinction of the four concept types (sortal, relational, functional, individual) is crucial since definiteness phenomena under discussion can be explained. Therefore, the interaction of the four concept types with the four definiteness strategies plays a central role in this book. This series explores issues of mental representation, linguistic structure and representation, and their interplay. The research presented in this series is grounded in the idea explored in the Collaborative Research Center 'The structure of representations in language, cognition and science' (SFB 991) that there is a universal format for the representation of linguistic and cognitive concepts.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aPolish. 4aSlavic languages. 4aarticleless languages. 4adefinite articles. 4ain-definite articles. 4atheory of Concept Types and Determination. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / General.2bisacsh  aCollaborative Research Center.  aConcept Types and Determination.  aDie Struktur von Repräsentationen in Sprache, Kognition und Wissenschaft.  aEnglish.  aFilip's approach.  aGerhard Schurz.  aGerman.  aHana Filip.  aHeinrich-Heine-Universität Düsseldorf.  aLambrecht.  aLaura Kallmeyer.  aLöbner's approach to definiteness.  aMathesius. 